{"cues": [{"duration": 2.8, "start": 0.12, "text": "Professor Dave again, let\u2019s graph some parabolas."}, {"duration": 4.32, "start": 9.66, "text": "Moving on to another conic section, we have\nthe parabola."}, {"duration": 5.49, "start": 13.99, "text": "This is where a plane intersects a cone, going\nthrough the edge of the cone and cutting down"}, {"duration": 5.93, "start": 19.48, "text": "to the base of that section, rather than across\nto the other side of the cone, like with circles"}, {"duration": 1.56, "start": 25.41, "text": "and ellipses."}, {"duration": 5.33, "start": 26.97, "text": "We learned quite a bit about parabolas earlier,\nwhen we first learned how to graph functions,"}, {"duration": 3.149, "start": 32.3, "text": "but let\u2019s learn the rigid definition."}, {"duration": 5.421, "start": 35.449, "text": "A parabola is the set of all points that are\nequidistant from a fixed point called the"}, {"duration": 4.439, "start": 40.87, "text": "focus, and a fixed line called the directrix."}, {"duration": 5.41, "start": 45.309, "text": "In other words, any point on this curve will\nbe just as far from the focus as it is from"}, {"duration": 3.561, "start": 50.719, "text": "this directrix at its closest point."}, {"duration": 5.169, "start": 54.28, "text": "This is different from something like an ellipse,\nwhere it\u2019s the sum of the distances from"}, {"duration": 2.68, "start": 59.449, "text": "two foci that remains constant."}, {"duration": 5.891, "start": 62.129, "text": "We also already know that parabolas are second\ndegree polynomials, but we only looked at"}, {"duration": 7.95, "start": 68.02, "text": "very simple examples like X squared, and others\nin vertex form that involve only known transformations"}, {"duration": 1.62, "start": 75.97, "text": "of X squared."}, {"duration": 5.52, "start": 77.59, "text": "What if we have something trickier, like negative\nX squared minus two X plus one."}, {"duration": 5.45, "start": 83.11, "text": "With this standard form, we can\u2019t readily\nidentify shifts or stretches that can be applied"}, {"duration": 1.6, "start": 88.56, "text": "to a simpler function."}, {"duration": 4.0, "start": 90.16, "text": "Instead, we can do one of two things."}, {"duration": 6.47, "start": 94.16, "text": "We can either rearrange the equation to get\nit into vertex form, or we can follow a series"}, {"duration": 5.5, "start": 100.63, "text": "of steps that will allow us to figure out\nwhere the vertex is, and other information"}, {"duration": 2.75, "start": 106.13, "text": "that will allow us to graph the function."}, {"duration": 3.26, "start": 108.88, "text": "Let\u2019s try the first way first."}, {"duration": 2.59, "start": 112.14, "text": "Remember when we learned how to complete the\nsquare?"}, {"duration": 5.73, "start": 114.73, "text": "That\u2019s exactly what we are going to do here,\nso that we can get this parabola in vertex"}, {"duration": 5.4, "start": 120.46, "text": "form, because once in vertex form, we can\njust identify all the transformations we need"}, {"duration": 5.149, "start": 125.86, "text": "to apply to a simple X squared curve to get\nthis particular parabola."}, {"duration": 5.45, "start": 131.009, "text": "Let\u2019s discuss how to do this to a generalized\nversion of a parabola first."}, {"duration": 6.451, "start": 136.459, "text": "Remember, from AX squared plus BX plus C,\nwe want to get it into this form, where we"}, {"duration": 7.6, "start": 142.91, "text": "have A out here, X minus H inside parentheses\nwhich is then squared, and then K out here."}, {"duration": 6.429, "start": 150.51, "text": "A, H, and K will then represent terms that\nstretch and shift the parabola so that it\u2019s"}, {"duration": 1.3, "start": 156.939, "text": "easy to graph."}, {"duration": 5.36, "start": 158.239, "text": "The first thing we need to do to get closer\nto this form is to factor an A out of the"}, {"duration": 1.881, "start": 163.599, "text": "first two terms."}, {"duration": 6.379, "start": 165.48, "text": "For AX squared we just lose the A, but for\nBX, we end up with B over A times X."}, {"duration": 3.041, "start": 171.859, "text": "Then, we complete the square."}, {"duration": 6.51, "start": 174.9, "text": "Remember, to do that, we take this term here,\ncut it in half, and then square it."}, {"duration": 3.48, "start": 181.41, "text": "That gives us B squared over four A squared."}, {"duration": 5.139, "start": 184.89, "text": "We add that inside the parenthetical term,\nbut we must realize that we are really adding"}, {"duration": 6.91, "start": 190.029, "text": "A times this term, since A is multiplying\nacross this sum, which means we also have"}, {"duration": 6.34, "start": 196.939, "text": "to subtract B squared over four A elsewhere\nin the expression, so that we don\u2019t change"}, {"duration": 2.21, "start": 203.279, "text": "the value of the expression."}, {"duration": 5.67, "start": 205.489, "text": "Then, this trinomial is a perfect square,\nwhich was the point of all this, so we express"}, {"duration": 4.131, "start": 211.159, "text": "it as X plus B over 2A quantity squared."}, {"duration": 7.0, "start": 215.29, "text": "Now, if we express this term as X minus negative\nB over 2A, we have this precisely in vertex"}, {"duration": 3.199, "start": 222.29, "text": "form for a parabola."}, {"duration": 4.87, "start": 225.489, "text": "We have an H and a K, which will allow us\nto find the vertex, and we have a stretch"}, {"duration": 2.05, "start": 230.359, "text": "value over here."}, {"duration": 7.771, "start": 232.409, "text": "Let\u2019s take our particular parabola and use\nthe A, B, and C values to evaluate H and K,"}, {"duration": 8.699, "start": 240.18, "text": "which will give us negative one and two as\nthe X and Y coordinates of the vertex respectively."}, {"duration": 6.381, "start": 248.879, "text": "Beyond this, A is negative one, which means\nthat the parabola opens downwards."}, {"duration": 5.509, "start": 255.26, "text": "And that\u2019s how we take a parabola in standard\nform and put it into vertex form, so that"}, {"duration": 1.781, "start": 260.769, "text": "it\u2019s easy to graph."}, {"duration": 4.95, "start": 262.55, "text": "Of course we don\u2019t have to derive this equation\nevery time, we can just complete the square"}, {"duration": 2.02, "start": 267.5, "text": "regularly with numbers."}, {"duration": 5.92, "start": 269.52, "text": "We just factor A out of the first two terms,\ncomplete the square, being careful to compensate"}, {"duration": 6.74, "start": 275.44, "text": "for this coefficient, change this to a binomial\nsquared, and there\u2019s our equation in vertex form."}, {"duration": 4.46, "start": 285.04, "text": "Now let\u2019s try the other way we mentioned,\nwhere we leave the equation as it is."}, {"duration": 4.67, "start": 289.51, "text": "The first step in this algorithm will be to\nfigure out whether the parabola opens upwards"}, {"duration": 1.48, "start": 294.18, "text": "or downwards."}, {"duration": 4.58, "start": 295.66, "text": "To do this, we look at A and see if it is\npositive or negative."}, {"duration": 3.049, "start": 300.24, "text": "If the coefficient is positive, it opens up."}, {"duration": 2.141, "start": 303.289, "text": "If negative, it opens down."}, {"duration": 4.89, "start": 305.43, "text": "In this case, we can take the coefficient\nas being negative one, so it opens down."}, {"duration": 2.439, "start": 310.32, "text": "The next step is to find the vertex."}, {"duration": 5.831, "start": 312.759, "text": "As we said, this will have an X coordinate\nequal to negative B over two A, which in this"}, {"duration": 6.479, "start": 318.59, "text": "case is equal to the negative of negative\ntwo over two times negative one, which all"}, {"duration": 2.391, "start": 325.069, "text": "comes out to negative one."}, {"duration": 5.19, "start": 327.46, "text": "Once we have that, we can plug it into the\nfunction to get the corresponding Y value,"}, {"duration": 3.019, "start": 332.65, "text": "which in this case will be two."}, {"duration": 4.911, "start": 335.669, "text": "This confirms that the vertex is at the point\nnegative one, two."}, {"duration": 5.399, "start": 340.58, "text": "From here, we could get additional points\nby finding the X and Y intercepts."}, {"duration": 5.521, "start": 345.979, "text": "The X intercepts are the points where the\nfunction is equal to zero, so we can find"}, {"duration": 3.539, "start": 351.5, "text": "them by setting the function equals to zero."}, {"duration": 5.321, "start": 355.039, "text": "In this particular case, in order to solve\nthis, we have to use the quadratic formula."}, {"duration": 4.75, "start": 360.36, "text": "We went over this in a previous tutorial,\nwhich you can check out now in case you forgot"}, {"duration": 1.89, "start": 365.11, "text": "how to use this."}, {"duration": 7.03, "start": 367.0, "text": "Otherwise, we just plug in all the coefficients,\nand when we get the answers, we can just evaluate"}, {"duration": 5.71, "start": 374.03, "text": "these to the nearest tenth so that we can\nget an approximate value to graph."}, {"duration": 4.959, "start": 379.74, "text": "The Y intercept will be much easier to get,\nbecause that is the value of the function"}, {"duration": 5.391, "start": 384.699, "text": "when X equals zero, or the point where the\nfunction crosses the Y axis."}, {"duration": 3.77, "start": 390.09, "text": "We plug in zero, and we should get one."}, {"duration": 6.61, "start": 393.86, "text": "Lastly, we could find the axis of symmetry,\nwhich will be X equals negative B over two"}, {"duration": 4.159, "start": 400.47, "text": "A, just to make sure everything looks right."}, {"duration": 5.641, "start": 404.629, "text": "So now we have the vertex, some intercepts,\nand a line, and that\u2019s all we really need"}, {"duration": 5.57, "start": 410.27, "text": "to generate a reasonable sketch of this function."}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 415.84, "text": "We now have a variety of ways to graph parabolas,\nand not just the easy kind."}, {"duration": 6.359, "start": 420.96, "text": "We can graph parabolas in vertex form by applying\ntransformations, or we can even graph parabolas"}, {"duration": 6.44, "start": 427.319, "text": "in standard form by completing the square,\nor finding various points on the curve."}, {"duration": 6.56, "start": 433.76, "text": "Parabolas are tremendously useful in physics, because\nprojectile motion always follows parabolic paths."}, {"duration": 4.36, "start": 440.32, "text": "Physics is awesome, though we can\u2019t get\nsidetracked just now, as we have one more"}, {"duration": 1.351, "start": 444.699, "text": "conic section to go."}, {"duration": 2.11, "start": 446.05, "text": "But first, let\u2019s check comprehension."}], "video_id": "hvJkCMzFiX8"}